04726nam a22005655i 9780226532615DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226532615  a(DE-B1597)524384  a(OCoLC)1135592261  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHV6432b.M58 2011eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a973.9312221 aMitchell, W. J. T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCloning Terror :bThe War of Images, 9/11 to the Present /cW. J. T. Mitchell. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b8 color plates, 38 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface. For a War on Error -- t1. War Is Over (If You Want It) -- t2. Cloning Terror -- t3. Clonophobia -- t4. Autoimmunity Picturing Terror -- t5. The Unspeakable and the Unimaginable -- t6. Biopictures -- t7. The Abu Ghraib Archive -- t8. Documentary Knowledge and Image Life -- t9. State of the Union, or Jesus Comes to Abu Ghraib -- tConclusion. A Poetics of the Historical Image -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe phrase “War on Terror” has quietly been retired from official usage, but it persists in the American psyche, and our understanding of it is hardly complete. Nor will it be, W. J. T Mitchell argues, without a grasp of the images that it spawned, and that spawned it. Exploring the role of verbal and visual images in the War on Terror, Mitchell finds a conflict whose shaky metaphoric and imaginary conception has created its own reality. At the same time, Mitchell locates in the concept of clones and cloning an anxiety about new forms of image-making that has amplified the political effects of the War on Terror. Cloning and terror, he argues, share an uncanny structural resemblance, shuttling back and forth between imaginary and real, metaphoric and literal manifestations. In Mitchell’s startling analysis, cloning terror emerges as the inevitable metaphor for the way in which the War on Terror has not only helped recruit more fighters to the jihadist cause but undermined the American constitution with “faith-based” foreign and domestic policies. Bringing together the hooded prisoners of Abu Ghraib with the cloned stormtroopers of the Star Wars saga, Mitchell draws attention to the figures of faceless anonymity that stalk the ever-shifting and unlocatable “fronts” of the War on Terror. A striking new investigation of the role of images from our foremost scholar of iconology, Cloning Terror will expand our understanding of the visual legacy of a new kind of war and reframe our understanding of contemporary biopower and biopolitics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aOral communicationxPolitical aspects. 0aOral communicationxPsychological aspects. 0aVisual communicationxPolitical aspects. 0aVisual communicationxPsychological aspects. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009vArt and the war. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPsychological aspects. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009, in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aterrorist, terrorism, war, wartime, images, imagery, 9/11, history, historical, 20th, 21st, century, contemporary, modern, present day, america, american, united states, usa, psychology, psychological, memory, tragedy, clones, theory, theoretical, academic, scholarly, research, metaphorical, domestic, policy, government, biopower, biopolitics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226532615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/